Miltary coup

ChiratchayaJanpechpanao

Introduction

This project examines how political and demographic factors are related to the number of successful military coups in sub-Saharan Africa. Variables considered include years of military oligarchy, number of political parties, population size, number of elections, regime duration, and country size. All analyses were conducted using R Studio.

Initial Data Analysis

The dataset contains 47 observations and 9 variables describing political and demographic characteristics across countries. The variables fall into two main groups:

Factor variables:

miltcoup: Number of successful military coups from independence to 1989 numregim: Number of regime types parties: Number of legal political parties in 1993 oligarchy: Number of years the country was ruled by a military oligarchy from independence to 1989 numelec: Total number of legislative and presidential elections Numeric variables: popn: Population (in millions) in 1989 size: Land area in thousand square kilometers A quick inspection shows that the variable Pollib contains 5 missing values, while pctovote has 6 missing values, which will need to be addressed before conducting further analysis.

Key Points: Exploring the data visually and statistically helps detect relationships between variables. Single-variable models show that the duration of oligarchy has the strongest influence on coups.

Visualization

Initial exploration included scatterplots and boxplots to understand how each variable relates to the number of coups, as well as correlation checks to see if predictors are dependent. Boxplots showing relationship between number of coups and predictors like oligarchy and population.

Figure 2: Scatterplot matrix illustrating relationships among all predictors.

## [1] "Look for dependency"

Finding the disitribution

A preliminary look at the outcome variable suggests that it follows a Poisson-like distribution. The values are non-negative counts, the mean and variance are roughly aligned, and the distribution is right-skewed with many countries showing low counts and only a few countries showing higher values. This pattern is consistent with what we expect from a Poisson process, where events occur independently and infrequently over time.

Building six different models with poisson as distribution with one predictor

I fitted six Poisson regression models to predict the number of military coups (miltcoup) using a single predictor each. Both years under military oligarchy and number of regime types were strong positive predictors, indicating that countries with longer military rule or more regime changes tend to experience more coups. Population also had a small positive effect. In contrast, country size, number of elections, and number of parties were weaker or non-significant predictors. Overall, oligarchy and regime variability are the most important factors in explaining coup frequency in this dataset.

'Create 6 possible models with one predictor only'
## [1] "Create 6 possible models with one predictor only"
mdl<-glm(miltcoup~oligarchy,family=poisson,data=africa)
mdl2<-glm(miltcoup~parties,family=poisson,data=africa)
mdl3<-glm(miltcoup~popn,family=poisson,data=africa)
mdl4<-glm(miltcoup~size,family=poisson,data=africa)
mdl5<-glm(miltcoup~numelec,family=poisson,data=africa)
mdl6<-glm(miltcoup~numregim,family=poisson,data=africa)

Model containing all predictors

A full Poisson regression model shows that years under military oligarchy is the strongest predictor of military coups, while other variables (parties, population, size, elections, regime types) are not significant. The model fits well (residual deviance = 48.5, AIC = 136.2) and there is no overdispersion (dispersion 1.01). Comparing AIC values confirms that oligarchy alone explains most of the variation in coup counts.

mdlFULL<-glm(miltcoup~.,family=poisson,data=africa)

AIC MODE

Using AIC-based stepwise selection, the final Poisson model for military coups (miltcoup) retained oligarchy and numelec as predictors, achieving the lowest AIC (130.8). Years under military oligarchy has the strongest effect (Estimate = 0.133, p < 0.001), while the number of elections also contributes positively (Estimate = 0.106, p = 0.019). The model fits well (residual deviance = 51.16 on 44 degrees of freedom) and performs similarly to the full model.
